<br>
Figured I'd post a as-I-understand-it on how mob aggro works, with an eye toward helping mitigate the challenges that warriors face with aggro before/during fights.<br>
<br>
What is &quot;aggro&quot;:  The mob attacks or TRIES TO ATTACK exactly ONE player at any instant in time, the one it &quot;hates&quot; the most AND meets all the other criteria (detailed in a bit).  The mob also has an &quot;aggro list&quot;, which included everybody it &quot;knows of&quot; that it would kill if it could.<br>
<br>
What generates the aggro list:  <br>
-Attacking a mob OR having a mob spontaneously frenzy and attack will add a player to the mob's aggro list (obviously).  <br>
-Moving close enough to a mob that it &quot;notices&quot; you but doesn't attack, or in some cases simply /con-ing a mob will usually add a player to the mob's hate list.  <br>
-Doing ANYTHING beneficial to a player on the mobs hate list will add the benefactor to the list as well, at apparently any distance from the mob (in same zone of course), and this is *recursive*.  i.e. hate lists can grow geometrically as players buff/heal/etc. each other, even at long distances from the mob in question.  This is probably why bards always got zone wide DTed/HTed in PoF... never let a pull get away. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
-Having something beneficial done to you by a player on a hate list will *NOT* add you to the hate list however- bards do not transfer aggro to people their songs benefit, for instance.<br>
-Mobs transfer aggro lists to other mobs they are &quot;allied&quot; with AND are in close proximity, can happen when pathing or at static spawn points.<br>
-Mob's aggro lists are typically cleared when they return to their spawn location IF they are static spawns; roamer mobs (non-static spawns) aggro lists appear to decay over time (this was changed at some point to prevent the zone-wide trains that occured in FV, WW, etc. I think).  Seems to be about 5 minutes, but may vary by zone/mob/etc?<br>
-note: the mob aggro list is NOT (necessarily) the same as it's rampage list!<br>
<br>
What is &quot;hate&quot;:  There's kind of two &quot;types&quot; of hate: the instantaneous type that causes a mob to be attacking a particular player at a given time, and a more general &quot;hate list&quot; number, which appears to be a numerical value assigned to each and every player (and pet and NPC) on the mobs aggro list.  Just to make things complicated, there also appear to be modifiers to the numerical values on the hate list as well.<br>
<br>
What generates instantaneous hate:  Some actions/events generate &quot;special&quot; aggro that cause the mob to ignore it's regular hate list.  The two most common examples of this are low health aggro and one I like to call &quot;screw u trying to log out at less than 10 seconds to camp&quot;.  Both of these will cause mobs that are able to attack the target to ignore all else to do so.  Low health aggro appears to overcome the screw-u variety, so if your buddies are dying you might still get camped out in time...<br>
<br>
What generates numerical hate:  Pretty straightforward; anything that damages, debuffs, or inconviences a mob generates a specific amount of &quot;hate&quot;, as do direct hate generation procs/effects (enraging blow).  Also, doing beneficial things like buffing, healing, or helping to players/pets the npc would like to kill (are on it's aggro list) generates a set amount of hate as well.  Combinations of effects (DD + dot + debuff for instance) will typically generate more hate than simple DD effects.  Effects that are resisted, or even that the mob is totally immune to, still generate hate.  Don't know if fizzled or out-of-range beneficial spells cast on hated players add to the hate list or not (suspect they don't).  Some spells and abilities (ench/sk horrifying/glamourous vision, AA skills spell casting sublety, etc.) modify the amount of hate generated that is actually applied.<br>
<br>
What affects numerical hate:  Numerical hate once generated can be modified by only a few methods;  blur/atone, jolt, concussion, evade, taunt, FD/dying/zoning, and (probably) time.  Blur/atone clears a mob's hate list entirely.  Concussion and jolt add a negative number to that players total hate on the TARGET mob's list.  Evade: If the rogue is first or second on the hate list, his amount of hate is reduced to the point where he is third on the list. If the rogue is third on the list or lower, hate is reduced by a set numerical amount<br>
(edited, thx posters below).  FD/dying/zoning clears that player from the mobs hate list.  Finally, a SUCCESSFUL taunt places the taunter a very small amount above the highest previous player on the mobs hate list; a failed taunt doesn't nothing.  Let me repeat- a successful taunt can take a player from zero hate to the highest location on the list numerically.  Use your imagination.<br>
<br>
How does a mob decide to attack:  A mob has a chance, probably checked once per tick OR once per event (like the player /con'ing) to  attack when a player is in it's &quot;aggro radius&quot; and the mob &quot;knows the player is there&quot;.  A mob will (obviously) also attack when an offensive spell/attack is directed at it IN ITS AGGRO RADIUS; rangers with certain very long range bows and arrows can risk banning by sitting beyond mob aggro range and killing said mobs without the mob attacking back... don't do that.<br>
<br>
What determines the mob's aggro radius:  Bunch of things, but it seems to be a function of zone, mob-specific value, and mob level vs. player level, line of sight, mob facing, and elevation differences.  Some abilities/spells (sneak, lull/harmony, etc) affect this distance, either on a player or the mob itself.<br>
<br>
How does the mob decide who to (try to) attack:  The target of the mob's attention is the player/pet/npc with the highest &quot;instantaneous&quot; hate.  This number is based on the numerical hate value, plus exceptions and modifiers.<br>
<br>
Exceptions:<br>
-IF it can reach them, a player with &quot;low health&quot; will be attacked first.<br>
-Players within ~5-10 seconds of camping and within what seems to be either spell or detection range.<br>
-If the mob is PLAYER rooted (or blind?) it will typically attack the nearest player; this does NOT happen with zero movement or permarooted mobs...<br>
-If the mob becomes uncharmed, it appears it's aggro list is cleared with the exception of the charm-er, who has a significant amount of aggro applied.<br>
-Mobs will not typically not try to attack players who are invunerable to damage (DA/DB, etc) no matter what their hate, health, etc. is.<br>
<br>
Modifiers:<br>
-sitting in the &quot;presence&quot; (probably detection or melee range)  of an aggro mob appears to multiply the numerical value of hate that mob has for the sit-er significantly.<br>
-distance has a very strong multiplier to numerical mob hate.  Some mobs have what is known as &quot;undead aggro&quot;, which is nearly entirely dominated by distance from (apparently) player center to mob center.  This is why attacking from max melee distance helps MTs control aggro so well.  Some mobs (dain) are apparently NOT as sensitive to distance, which makes MTing them a pain.<br>
-some mobs may have an additional modifier to hate generated by healing; i.e. numerical aggro caused by healing is increased by some fraction vs. it's baseline value.<br>
-there is some suggestion that mobs might pick &quot;weaker&quot; targets preferentially, all other things being equal, never figured out a good way to test this tho.<br>
<br>
I think most of the above is accurate, at least it seems consistent with what I've seen/experienced so far.  Using the above information and observations, you can do some really elegant finessing with pulls, aggro management, etc... IF everybody knows what they are doing and pays attention. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
