I have never seen /con give any form of aggro whatsoever. Simple experiment: con a non-kos mob repeatedly, it will not attack you. Con a kos mob while nearby &amp; invis. It will not attack you. Con a green kos mob (that doesn't normally attack) while nearby. It will not attack you.<br>
<br>
<br>
Picking on weaker characters:<br>
<br>
Mobs can be attuned to dislike characters based on their religion, race, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> or class</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. I've had some annoying experiences with my enchanter trying to talk to quest NPCs or buying from merchants.<br>
<br>
Hail, Troll!<br>
<br>
&quot;High Elves like you are an affront to my senses&quot;<br>
<br>
*cast Illusion Troll*<br>
<br>
Hail, Troll!<br>
<br>
&quot;Enchanters like you are an affront to my senses&quot;<br>
<br>
It would make sense that once you walk into a mob's awareness range that your initial hate setting is based upon your faction standing with the mob.<br>
<br>
<br>
Awareness:<br>
<br>
PCs only seem to generate &quot;awareness aggro&quot; when the mob doesn't have much hate on someone. The common proof of awareness aggro is when a faction'd mob is pulled by a bunch of sitting people, and dies, every kos person that was sitting gets a faction hit! However, it can be shown that awareness aggro <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> doesn't</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> happen if the mob is sufficiently angry. The most common example is CRing nagafen. If a lvl 52 person angers nagafen, people can CR with impunity, including lvl 53+ people who would normally be sneezed out of the zone instantly upon making the aggro list. Other proof comes when a pet is tanking a mob. If a single pet is tanking a mob and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> anyone</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the mob is angry at comes within melee range, the mob will start attacking the PC. However, if the pet has built up aggro and a new PC enters range, they won't get hit since they didn't generate awareness aggro.<br>
<br>
<br>
Hate modifiers:<br>
<br>
There are several effects that don't generate hate, but instead modify the hate list. This may cause the mob to attack someone not on the hate list, or possibly to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not attack</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> someone who is on the hate list.<br>
<br>
Sitting is a hate modifier, not a hate generator. This can be tested as follows (I have not done it):<br>
<br>
Rune an enchanter and tash a low level mob. Have a warrior come along and do nothing but taunt. On a successful taunt, the mob should still attack the enchanter because while the warrior is still at the top of the hate list, sitting creates a hate modifier that causes the mob to continue to attack the enchanter.<br>
<br>
Proximity (aka lazy) aggro:<br>
<br>
Distance is a hate modifier. Some fun examples are that a rooted mob will always attack the closest person on the aggro list, no matter what the hate level is. Some mobs, particularly undead, also have a tendancy to attack people close to them. Being far enough away from a mob can actually cause you to drop below the attack threshhold, and the mob will return home. You are still on the hate list, though, because if you come back within range it will come back after you (and bring friends, if it's social!).<br>
<br>
Low Health aggro.<br>
